Web Security - Access Control
Access Control
What is Access Control?
Access control is a security mechanism that determines who is allowed to access specific resources and what actions they are permitted to perform within an application.

Access control works together with two other important security mechanisms:

Authentication – verifies the identity of a user.
Session Management – keeps track of authenticated users across multiple requests.
Access Control – decides what authenticated users are allowed to do.
For example:

Authentication
      │
      ▼
User is Soham
      │
      ▼
Session Created
      │
      ▼
Access Control
      │
      ▼
Can Soham access /admin?
Without proper access control, any authenticated user might be able to access resources belonging to other users or administrative functionality.

Broken Access Control is one of the most critical vulnerabilities in modern web applications and consistently ranks among the top security risks in the OWASP Top 10. PortSwigger also highlights that broken access controls are common because access control rules are complex and easy to implement incorrectly.

Why is Access Control Important?
Imagine an online banking application.

Different users have different permissions.

User	Permissions
Customer	View own account
Manager	Approve loans
Administrator	Manage users
If the bank only verifies that a person is logged in, but never checks what they are allowed to do, every customer could potentially approve loans or delete accounts.

Authentication alone is not enough.

Authorization (Access Control) must also be enforced.

Types of Access Control
There are three primary types of access control vulnerabilities.

1. Vertical Access Control
Vertical access control restricts functionality based on user roles.

Example:

Administrator
│
├── Delete Users
├── Manage Products
├── View Reports
└── Configure Website

Regular User
│
├── Buy Products
├── Edit Profile
└── View Orders
Only administrators should access:

/admin
If a normal user gains access to administrator functionality, it is called:

Vertical Privilege Escalation
Example:

Normal User

↓

Accesses

/admin

↓

Deletes Users

↓

Vertical Privilege Escalation
Common Causes
1. Unprotected Admin URLs
Example:

/admin
The application simply forgets to check whether the current user is an administrator.

Anyone can visit:

/admin
This was our Lab 1.

2. Security Through Obscurity
Developers hide the admin page:

/administrator-panel-x91k4
instead of protecting it.

The URL leaks inside:

JavaScript
robots.txt
HTML source
API responses
Attackers discover it.

This was Lab 2.

3. Parameter-Based Access Control
Applications store the user's role in client-controlled data such as:

Cookie
Hidden Field
Query Parameter
JSON
Example:

Cookie:

Admin=false
Attacker changes it to

Admin=true
Now the application believes the attacker is an administrator.

This was Lab 3.

4. Mass Assignment (Role Modification)
Some applications expose sensitive fields in API requests.

Example:

{
    "email":"abc@test.com",
    "roleid":1
}
Attacker changes:

roleid:2
The application automatically updates the user's role.

This was Lab 4.

5. URL-Based Access Control Bypass
This was today's lab and one of the most interesting examples of broken access control due to platform misconfiguration. PortSwigger explains that some frameworks support non-standard headers like X-Original-URL and X-Rewrite-URL, which can override the requested URL if the backend trusts them.

The Architecture
Many applications sit behind a reverse proxy.

Browser
    │
    ▼
Reverse Proxy
(Nginx / Apache / IIS)
    │
Checks URL
    │
    ▼
Backend Application
The reverse proxy acts like a security guard.

Normal Request
GET /admin
The proxy checks the URL.

/admin

↓

Blocked

↓

403 Forbidden
The request never reaches the backend.

The Vulnerability
Some backend frameworks trust special headers such as:

X-Original-URL
X-Rewrite-URL
Originally, these headers were designed for URL rewriting.

If the backend trusts these headers but the reverse proxy only checks the request path, the attacker can make both systems interpret the request differently.

Exploitation
Instead of requesting

GET /admin
the attacker sends

GET /

X-Original-URL: /admin
Now the systems disagree.

Reverse Proxy sees

/
Backend sees

/admin
The request reaches the admin panel even though the proxy attempted to block it.

Visual Flow
Client
   │
GET /
X-Original-URL: /admin
   │
   ▼
Reverse Proxy

Sees "/"

↓

Allows

↓

Backend

Reads

X-Original-URL: /admin

↓

Returns Admin Panel
Why It Happens
The application trusts client-controlled rewrite headers.

Access control exists only in the reverse proxy.

The backend performs no authorization check.

This creates an Access Control Bypass.

Real-World Impact
Successful exploitation may allow attackers to:

Access hidden administrator pages
Delete users
Modify administrator settings
Access confidential information
Execute privileged functionality
Prevention
Never trust X-Original-URL or X-Rewrite-URL from external users.
Strip rewrite headers before forwarding requests.
Enforce authorization in the backend application.
Never rely solely on reverse proxy URL filtering.
2. Horizontal Access Control
Horizontal access control restricts users from accessing resources belonging to other users.

Example:

User A

↓

/my-account?id=101
Attacker changes:

/my-account?id=102
Now the attacker accesses another user's account.

This is called:

Horizontal Privilege Escalation
PortSwigger also notes that this is a classic example of an Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) vulnerability.

3. Context-Dependent Access Control
Sometimes access depends on the application's current state rather than user roles.

Example:

Shopping Cart

↓

Checkout

↓

Payment Completed
After payment:

Modify Cart
should not be allowed.

If the application allows users to return and modify the cart after payment, context-dependent access control is broken.

Common Causes of Broken Access Control
Missing authorization checks
Predictable URLs
Security through obscurity
Client-side role storage
IDOR vulnerabilities
Platform misconfiguration
Trusting HTTP headers
Multi-step workflow flaws
Referer-based authorization
URL matching discrepancies
Method-based access control issues
